The Numenorian strength and power were impossible for the men of the South to challenge directly, so they resorted to guerrilla warfare. Attacking from the shadows with poison arrows and ambushing those who could be killed quickly and silently. This is likely where the first ideas of the Haradrim as an ‘honorless’ and ‘savage’ people first were born, as these tactics were considered deplorable by the Numenorians. After the fall of Numenor it was Lord Fuinor who saw the value in turning the Hasarii into a secret cult of enforcers. Through them, the rule of Sauron has become unassailable. While they began as a group that stood for the freedom of Harad, they are now a device of the Dark Lord and his proxy rulers.

When the Hasarii are called to the battlefield they gather as a sinister shadow of the main host, setting traps and stalking the roads and paths of the enemy. In open battle, the teachings of Sauron come alive the sadistic depravity of the Hasarii is on full display. It takes men of great courage to stand up in the face of what the Hasarii unleash, the sight of a tormented comrade might drive some to flee, only to be caught and taken as a prisoner of war into the horrid terror of the Hasarii headquarters.

The Blades prefer to fight up close with their victims, springing from the shadows in a flurry of attacks before vanishing into darkness. Twin blades dipped in snake venom ensure that even a small bite of the blade means agonizing death.
Hasharii Shadows.DescrShort: Lightly armoured assassins who are masters of stealth and armed with powerful composite bows.

Troll-men Warriors.Descr:
The humans that live in Far Harad are a strange and mysterious people. Some question whether they are some product of unholy magic or a cross between man and the evil spirits that roam the vast deserts. Their eyes are white and their skin a dark hue, they tower over other Southrons and somehow manage to carve out a life in one of the most inhospitable places on Middle Earth. Surely such things are unnatural? The truth that is more likely is that these folk are simply another example of mankind’s persistence and willingness to accept hardship. The world is a vast place, and the distinction of ‘Troll-Men’ is likely a way for the simple-minded to make sense of what they cannot understand.

The Troll-men of Far Harad are indeed brutal in war, living in the harshest wilderness will harden a people to a patient they may be indistinguishable from a cunning predator. These mighty people have mastered the craft of taming the Mumakil and have established trade with the Muhad for these powerful monsters. The Troll-men have a great sense of personal honor in combat, and discipline that comes from surviving the wastelands. They craft their own weapons from hardened bone sharp as steel. They hunt with javelins and despise the bow as a weapon, claiming it is the tool of lesser men. Whether they are a product of exotic climate or dark sorcery Troll-men represent a deadly threat on the battlefield.

REQUIRES BARREN REGION
Troll-men Warriors.DescrShort: Fearsome tribesmen from the distant reaches of Far Harad, armed with heavy blades and large wooden shields.\n\nREQUIRES BARREN REGION

Troll-men Hunters.Descr: The deserts, forests, and savannas of Far Harad hold a plethora of dangerous creatures. Mûmakil being the most well known and mightiest of these. All life here is utterly dependent upon the whims of the rains. The vast herds of the savanna undertake great migrations during times of drought, meaning anything or anyone who depends on them for food are also on the move quite often. Only the hardiest of peoples can survive here. The Troll Men of this land thrive in this exotic and harsh environment. In fact, it is they who capture and train adolescent Mûmakil to be the war machines that the Haradrim are famous for. The secrets of this training are a matter of great pride and amongst these tribes. The act of taking a young Mûmak from it's mother requires a bravery and strength unlike anything the Men of the West have ever seen. Most tribes field specialized teams of hunters whose main purpose is the acquisition of Mûmakil. These Troll Men wield their spears quite expertly as they have all needed to defend their lives from the various dangers of the Haradwaith. They have also found that the best tactic for bringing an angry Mûmak down is massed volleys of javelins. During the many conflicts with the Men of Gondor, the Haradrim have found that the same tactics which ensure their tribes' survival are actually quite effective against the heavily armoured cavalry of Dol Amroth. The addition of a shield to their kit, while not very useful on the hunt, helps ensure their survival on the battlefield.\n\nREQUIRES BARREN REGION
Troll-men Hunters.DescrShort: Fearsome tribesmen from the distant reaches of Far Harad, armed with deadly throwing spears.\n\nREQUIRES BARREN REGION

Troll-men Champions.Descr: Troll-men champions are the most dangerous men who walk beneath the southern sky. Their might and power are unequaled by any of Sauron’s mortal servants. They carry massive weapons of bleached bone and masks made from the skulls of those who stray into their lands uninvited. These warriors guard the Mumakil Graveyard in Far Harad, a holy place to the Troll-men. Each champion must venture deep into the Graveyard to commune with their ancestors as part of their right of passage. This may be how Sauron came to influence these folk and bring them into the fold, as Sauron is known as the Necromancer, and these people trust the words of the dead. It seems plausible that the Deceiver whispers his lies to these people from the Mumak Graveyard, such a deplorable thing would suit the Dark Lord. \n\nREQUIRES BARREN REGION
Troll-men Champions.DescrShort: Mighty tribesmen from the distant reaches of Far Harad, armed with heavy two-handed blades.\n\nREQUIRES BARREN REGION

Muhad Beastmasters.Descr:
All across the great Haradwaith; tribes form great collectives and communities around natural resources, fertile farmland, and the coastline of the Harnen. The Empire is built upon these masses and by its own laws it enforces this kind of consolidation of the masses. The exception to this rule is the Muhad. Perhaps the oldest of tribes that dot the more wild and untamed lands, the Muhad are a nation of primitive hunters and herdsmen that practice the same traditions as the savage ancestors that first migrated to Harad in the First Age. Surviving off the land and wildlife that call it home, protecting safer routes to the oasis of the desert, passing on the secrets of the savannah to the next generation.

The Muhad are skilled hunters and renowned for their ability to train horses and camels, even the mighty Mumakil can be tamed to be a beast of burden by these masters of wild craft. The Muhad are therefore an extremely valuable asset to the Serpent Lords of Harad, and through careful negotiation and patient cunning, the Muhad have gone from being an antagonist of Harad to its most powerful of the servile tribes.

The tithe of men the Serpent Lord demands of his loyal tribes can be paid in beasts by the Muhad. Instead of men, they bring their trained animals to augment the Serpent Lord's armies, and a trained horse is worth more than ten warriors in Harad! The Muhad have another privilege they have made for themselves; as they are the ones who know the safest paths through the deserts, they have established the trade roads that weave throughout the vast South. No goods are moved in Harad without the Muhad guiding them, effectively making them a ‘guild’ of commerce.

Beastmasters are skilled riders and prefer camels instead of horses for their longevity in the desert and for their greater intelligence. The smell and sounds of a camel can also spook horses who have never trained with them, and this can be an advantage when facing other mounted troops.

REQUIRES BARREN REGION
Muhad Beastmasters.DescrShort: Light camel unit armed with javelins and a mace. Frightens horses.\n\nREQUIRES BARREN REGION

Mumakil.Descr:
Of all the great beasts that roam Middle Earth the Mumakil reigns supreme as the most powerful of all creatures. Standing ten stories tall and boasting the strength of one thousand men, the mighty Mumak cannot be matched by any other living creature. To behold such a magnificent animal is to step back to a more primordial Age, nothing alive in this time rivals these beasts, and the enemies of Harad quake with fear knowing such raw power can be brought down upon them.

The Serpent Lord has declared that all Mumakil on Middle-Earth belong to him. As such; the tribes that hunt these creatures are sanctioned by His Majesty and must provide adequate tribute for each beast they slay. This tribute is taken in the form of trained Mumakil, captured by the Troll-Men of Far Harad and disciplined by the Muhad Beastmasters. It has taken generations to raise herds of Mumakil that can be trained, but by the sweat and blood of their labors, the savage tribes of the South have delivered unto the Serpent Lord, Emperor of all Harad, the greatest weapons in the world!

The sheer force these breasts can unleash is awesome to behold! With one sweep of its great tusks, the Mumak can send dozens of warriors soaring to their inglorious deaths. The most valiant of knights can be crushed in an instant, mount and all, beneath its mighty foot! Even Trolls would be trampled into bloody heaps if faced with the charge of a raging Mumak! The power of Harad is made manifest in such great creatures. No living warrior can stand before these monsters and hope to prevail…

REQUIRES HARADRIM WASTES
Mumakil.DescrShort: Huge and terrifying animals carrying Haradrim archers on their backs. Frightens most infantry as well as cavalry.\n\nREQUIRES HARADRIM WASTES

Loke Rim Bodyguard.Descr: Foremost among the Lôke-Rim are the Lôke-Rim Bodyguards, the elite halberdiers of Rhûn and some of the finest soldiers of the East. Clad in golden steel plate armour, scale armour, and steel chain mail, all the while wielding long and deadly halberds, the Lôke-Rim Bodyguards are an imposing force on the battlefield. Their imposing halberds allows them to stand firm against any foe, protecting their leader at all costs. Their presence on the battlefield gives incredible strength to the Lôke-Khans army and is a true sight to behold. While very capable of frontal assaults, these men are best used to defend their leader or to hold firm against an enemy tide.
Loke Rim Bodyguard.DescrShort: Very heavily armoured elite halberdiers protecting their General.

Daritai Clansmen.Descr: The various warlords of Rhûn each control large swaths of land and demand the loyalty of their followers. One of the clans are the Darïtaï who are loyal to the Lôke-Khan of Mistrand and the Dragon Cult. Dwelling in large settlements on the sea of Rhûn, the Darïtaï are perhaps the most urbanised clan out of those that dwell near Mordor. When the Lôke-Khan calls upon them they are to supply a quota of able bodied men based on past service and the required number of men. These clansmen go to war with an assortment of weapons. Typically they carry single edged blades and axes into battle as well as wooden shields. These men form the core army of the Dragon Cult and will serve to aid the Lôke-Khan in his mission of uniting Rhûn and forming an empire.
Daritai Clansmen.DescrShort: Lightly armoured and equipped with a sword, Clansmen are reliable support troops.

Daritai Hunters.Descr: The various warlords of Rhûn each control large swaths of land and demand the loyalty of their followers. One of the clans are the Darïtaï who are loyal to the Lôke-Khan of Mistrand and the Dragon Cult. Dwelling in large settlements on the sea of Rhûn, the Darïtaï are perhaps the most urbanised clan out of those that dwell near Mordor. When the Lôke-Khan calls upon them they are to supply a quota of able bodied men based on past service and the required number of men. Because of their urbanised nature and the lands they inhabit, the Darïtaï have become excellent archers, so they may defend their settlements from other, more nomadic clans. When not called upon to form part of the infantry, the clansmen are usually formed into archer groups. Using smaller composite bows, that can also be used from horseback, the clansmen archers possess considerable range and deadly impact. As side arms they carry similar weapons as their infantry counterparts.
Daritai Hunters.DescrShort: Used to hunting with a bow these troops are proficient with their bows, but will melt away quickly in melee.

Balchoth Tribesmen.Descr: The lands to the southeast of Mirkwood are inhabited by the remnants of the Balchoth. These warlike tribes invaded the west only to meet defeat at the hands of the fledging Rohirrim. Pushed back into the foothills along the Sea of Rhûn, their lust for battle has not diminished in the years since their invasion and defeat. Called on by Warlords and the Lôke-Khan as mercenaries, their tribesmen are ferocious warriors capable of ambushing an enemy and quickly disappearing into the shadows from whence they came. They carry menacing javelins, crude axes, and hand-scythes. Chiefly used for protecting archers or infantry flanks, they have been used by Warlords as a main battle line where there ferocity in a general melee was on display for all to see.
Balchoth Tribesmen.DescrShort: Made up from fierce Balchoth tribesmen, these excellent skirmishers hurl javelins at their foes, but can fight at close quarters if necessary.

Balchoth Spearmen.Descr: The lands to the southeast of Mirkwood are inhabited by the remnants of the Balchoth. These warlike tribes invaded the west only to meet defeat at the hands of the fledging Rohirrim. Pushed back into the foothills along the Sea of Rhûn, their lust for battle has not diminished in the years since their invasion and defeat. Called on by Warlords and the Lôke-Khan as mercenaries, these warriors excel at using the spears to bring down enemy horsemen but can also hold the line against most light infantry. However they are only lightly armoured themselves and should not be expected to hold against heavier foes for long without support
Balchoth Spearmen.DescrShort: Balchoth warriors protected by light armour and armed with spears.

Daritai Warriors.Descr: Aside from the Darïtaï clansmen that stand in reserve, there is also another, more professional, group within the clans. Darïtaï warriors are men raised from birth in the ways of battle, many of which have aspirations of entering into the sacred Lôke-Rim of the Dragon Cult. These warriors protect their own settlements when not in the service of the Lôke-Khan. Typically outfitted for war by the Dragon Cult, their weapons and equipment are passed on from generation to generation of clan warriors. As is their tradition, they forsake the safety of the shield and prefer to use their own agility and armour to protect them in combat. They carry an expertly crafted curved sabre into battle along with a guard sword which they use in their off hand and wield with such speed and lethality that it defends them like a shield. This guard sword is equipped with curved blade and a terrible claw at its end. Used in concert with the sabre, a Darïtaï warrior can create a masterful dance of death which few can resist. After the Lôke-Rim these men are some of the most valuable troops the Lôke-Khan possess.
Daritai Warriors.DescrShort: Disciplined swordsmen wearing light armour and an open helmet, and armed with two curved swords.

Arulad Dragonguard.Descr: The Arulad Dragonguard have broken their ties to family and hearth in the worship of dragons, swearing oaths of blood and fire and serving as the warrior elite of the clan. Trained to fight with their ferocious halberds, these warrior monks roam the battlefield in search of foes, keen to honour their reptilian deities through war. Though mighty, they are simple men of the East, equipped in scale mail of respectable craftsmanship, wielding the best weapons the tribal forges of their clansfolk can produce. Used as the cutting edge of a sword, these warriors might falter, but their lives will be well sold in the blood of your foes.
Arulad Dragonguard.DescrShort: These formidable troops are armed with six foot long halberds and are protected by lamellar armour.

Loke-Gamp Rim.Descr: Quite literally the bite of the Lôke-Khans army, the Lôke-Gamp Rim are highly trained pikemen and swordsmen. Wielding nine foot pike and halberd hybrids, they are the infantry which will ensure that the men of Rhûn are never defeated by the horses of Rohan again. Their job in battle is to close with the enemy under the protection of the Dragon's Fire and pin them in position, making the enemy susceptible to envelopment and destruction. They rely heavily on their pikes to provide the protection they need, keeping the enemy at a distance, and are therefore not as heavily armoured as the other infantry in the Lôke-Khans army.
Loke-Gamp Rim.DescrShort: Heavily armoured elite pikemen, their pikes make them effective against both foot and mounted foes.

Loke-Flag Rim.Descr: Heavily armoured and armed, the Lôke-Flag Rim are capable shock troops that are incredibly effective against armour. They wield heavy steel maces and axes and protect themselves with large shields. Primarily, their role is to protect the flanks of the Dragons Teeth, but they can also be used to soften the enemy up prior to main battle line engaging in melee. Of all the regiments the Dragon’s Skin is the most versatile, being capable of storming citadels or fighting on open battle plains. Used correctly they are nearly an unstoppable force.
Loke-Flag Rim.DescrShort: Very heavily armoured elite infantry, equipped with maces and a heavy shield.

Daritai Crossbowmen.Descr: For thousands of years the bow has been the weapon of choice for the men of Rhûn. However, against the might of enemies such as Dale, the elves of Mirkwood and the dwarves of Erebor the Dragon Cult feared such a weapon would be of little use and developed a new and deadlier weapon, the crossbow. Easy to use and even easier to train for, the Dragon Cult found it easier to arm their clansmen with the crossbow rather than trying to piece together groups of archers. However, with its ease of use, the crossbow of the Dragon Cult is still out ranged by their composite bows, placing its operators in greater danger as they close with the enemy. In an attempt to alleviate this crossbowman are typically outfitted in additional armour made of leather and steel similar to that of the clan warriors.
Daritai Crossbowmen.DescrShort: Slow to reload, but a potent and easy to use missile weapon firing powerful bolts.

Loke-Nar Rim.Descr: The Lôke-Nar Rim are some of the finest archers in Middle-earth. They possess large composite longbows with incredible range and power. In addition to their mastery of the bow they are also accomplished swordsmen. Furthermore, the Dragon Cult has developed oils that can be used to grant the power of fire to their arrows, and this fire burns even as the arrow flies through the air. As part of the Lôke-Khan’s combined arms strategy, they provide the missile screen required for the advance of the infantry and will ensure the expansion of the Empire. Any foe would do well not to underestimate them, lest they end up burning to death from one of their arrows.
Loke-Nar Rim.DescrShort: Lôke-Nar Rim are elite missile troops equipped with composite bow, sabre and golden steel plates.

Udege Marines.Descr: As the clans fall deeper into their worship of the Dragon Fire, their finest minds concoct new and powerful methods of bringing this flame to bear on their enemies. The Udege Marines represent the pinnacle of that research. Where once these hardy warriors brought volleys of javelins down upon their sea-faring enemies, they now bombard the field with flasks of the fierce flames. Whether it be science or magic, the outcome is a weapon that causes mass devastation, panic and disarray to enemy lines. Caution is advised to any who fight besides the crazed marines: should their aim falter then a grim and fiery death awaits any who get to close to their mark.\n\nREQUIRES COASTAL REGION
Udege Marines.DescrShort: Soldiers from the ships of the Udege clan, armed with swords and flasks of burning oil.\n\nREQUIRES COASTAL REGION

Arulad Dragonriders.Descr: Separated from family and home by oaths of blood and fire, the Arulad Dragonriders have brought fine eastern mounts to their service. Quick and fearless, these warriors serve as hardy raiders and a strong flanking force for the armies of Rhûn, able to keep pace with the swift Khandish riders to the south, and support the dreaded Easterling Kataphracts. Using their halberds as makeshift lances, once engaged these devotees of the dragon can smash their Dalish and Dorwinion counterparts from the saddle, but beware - their armour will not protect from a determined attack, and their horses will fall quickly to arrow fire. Use them as the first spear in your arsenal.
Arulad Dragonriders.DescrShort: Encased in lamellar and equipped with lances and sabres these warriors are formidable fighting machines.

Loke-Innas Rim.Descr: Foremost among the Lôke-Rim are the Lôke-Innas Rim, the heavy cavalry of the Khan and the finest cavalry in all of Middle-earth. Clad in golden steel plate armour, scale armour, and steel chain mail, all the while mounted upon massive war horses draped in armour, the Kataphracts are an imposing force on the battlefield. They charge into battle with long cavalry spears and carry with them menacing curved sabres. Their presence on the battlefield gives incredible strength to the Lôke-Khan’s army and hence provides the Will of the Dragon Regiments. While capable of frontal assaults, the Dragons Will is best utilized in concert with the other regiments. They provide the final envelopment of the enemy and the final devastating charge into their rear.
Loke-Innas Rim.DescrShort: Very heavily armoured elite cavalry and equipped with a lance and sabre.

Loke-Scion Rim.Descr: The Lôke-Scion Rim are perhaps the finest mainstream warriors that the Easterlings can field. They train with the mighty cultists and wear a similar fitting armour but are drilled in the use of the duel-headed spear and shield. With the men of Dorwinion, Dale and even Khand beginning to creep closer to Rhûn's border the decision was made to make a unit who could hold back the thundering hooves of these nations. The mighty men of the Scion are the answer. Woe will befall any foolish mount who strays amongst their well drilled ranks.
Loke-Scion Rim.DescrShort: Lôke-Scion Rim are elite troops equipped with spear, shield and golden steel plates.

Suriut Chariots.Descr: The Süri'ut are a confederation of tribes to the east of Rhûn that has not formally joined Sauron. Their people did not seek wealth, riches, land or glory and were not swayed by his promises. However, their latest leader (Sür), a man called Ja, seeks to expand his power and to make a vast empire. He has seen the strength which the Darïtaï and our leader wield and he has requested a military alliance! The Süri'ut are not great warriors but they are master craftsmen and they are fanatical about chariot races. As such, their chariots are second to none and vastly outclass the hay wagons of the Wainriders. Whilst Ja Sür cannot promise us any troops he has promised us these war chariots in exchange for riches and glory. We have trained our finest archers to use these great wagons and now we can ride across the plain as a thunder storm! Like the Lôke-Nar Rim, these chariots are also armed with the flaming arrows of the Dragon Cult. Our enemies will quake as the Empire of Rhûn expands!\n\nREQUIRES RHÛNNIC HEARTLANDS
Suriut Chariots.DescrShort: Elite archers mounted on swift Chariots.\n\nREQUIRES RHÛNNIC HEARTLANDS

Variag Nobles.Descr: Khand is a land of tribes and chieftains, greatest of these are the Variags. Men who have featured upon the history of the west only twice but fierce men nonetheless. They are a warrior people and hold honour and bravery high. The bravest and greatest warriors are chosen to defend the sons of the Variag Chieftain and ruling noblemen, however only those of Variag blood can join the ranks of the nobles bodyguards. Appearing on the battlefield as 'Variag Nobles', they are swift and deadly. They wield powerful bows and excellent swords and wear the finest armour that the smithies of the tribes can offer. Although this is heavy armour, it is not like the armour of Dol Amroth or the Lonely Mountain as it has been adapted for men of the saddle and affords them speed as well as protection. The pride of the Variags is reflected in these men and their finely honed skills in archery and swordsmanship from atop their mounts are held in high esteem throughout the tribes.
Variag Nobles.DescrShort: Excellent cavalry, clad in heavy armour and armed with keen blades and powerful bows.

Steppe Tribesmen.Descr: Although the Variags are the strongest of all the tribes of Khand, their numbers are still mainly made up of unskilled tribesmen, little more than peasants. Due to the harsh lifestyle of the steppes, these men are much stronger than the peasants of the men of the west but they are not a problem for even militia to deal with. Variags have a rich tradition of warfare and due to their mingling with Haradrim and Easterlings they have a strong hatred toward Gondor and their northern Rohirric allies. These men use that hatred and as such can survive in battle on their dark zealotry alone. When war is called, these men choose to march forward with a spear and a shield for protection, additionally, they carry a single volley of javelins. They wear little to no armour and should avoid frontline combat, being used as a last resort or as arrow fodder.
Steppe Tribesmen.DescrShort: Spear wielding peasantry equipped with very light armour.

Steppe Archers.Descr: Although the Variags are the strongest of all the tribes of Khand, their numbers mainly consist of unskilled tribesmen, little more than peasants. Due to the harsh lifestyle of the steppes, these men are much stronger than the peasants of the men of the west but they are not a problem for even militia to deal with. Variags have a rich tradition of warfare and due to their mingling with Haradrim and Easterlings they have a strong hatred toward Gondor and their northern Rohirric allies. These men use that hatred and as such can survive in battle on their dark zealotry alone. When war is called, these men choose to march forward with a bow and a shield for protection. They wear little to no armour and should avoid melee at all costs.
Steppe Archers.DescrShort: Basic archers of the steppes equipped with hunting bows and wearing little protection.

Marauders.Descr: Khand is a large country, stretching from the Ered Lithui down to the deserts of Near Harad and it is predominantly ruled over by the Variags. However there are bands of roaming mercenaries and bandits who terrorize the innocent clans folk of the steppes. Using cunning and a great deal of money, the Variags have managed to persuade these Marauders to focus their fury on the foes of the clans and they have since become powerful allies. They aren't well armoured and they aren't well organized but they are very fast, relatively cheap and perfect for picking off any fool who tries to run from the battlefield. Like vultures they prowl the field out of range of any real threat but ready to strike when a weakness opens up.
Marauders.DescrShort: Axe wielding horsemen, lightly armoured and swift.

Nomad Horsemen.Descr: These horsemen, drawn from all the tribes of Khand, form the bulk of the feared mounted hordes of Khand. Like all of the men of Khand they are proud and have been shaped by a warrior culture and have known the saddle since birth becoming fine horsemen. These men only wear medium armour and, instead of the heavy lances favoured by Khand's more elite cavalry, they use spears on the battlefield. One thing these men do have in abundance is speed, and they have mastered the hit and run tactic and will not easily tire. However, due to their relatively light equipment, these men will not survive in prolonged combat long and must use their speed and superior horsemanship to quickly disengage after delivering their stinging charges.
Nomad Horsemen.DescrShort: Medium horsemen armed with deadly spears and cavalry shields.

Khandish Raiders.Descr: Khand, lying south west of Rhûn, has been the traditional ally of the Easterlings since the time of the Wainriders. As such they supply mercenaries to the Warlords and the Lôke-Khan whenever asked. These take the form of Horsemen and adept archers. The Khandish Hunters are fast moving archers who form a perfect counter-part to the guard of the Easterlings. Outfitted with light leather lamellar and steel helmets Hunters carry composite bows and axes into battle. In times of need, the Hunters can be mounted and serve as cavalry where their skills rival those of the Lôke-Khans own elite cavalry. When mounted, these men act like a brutal hit and run unit and as such, their enemies have branded them 'Raiders' due to the frequency of the raids conducted by these grim men.
Khandish Raiders.DescrShort: These hardy bowmen have a fierce and unruly reputation.

Uushixia Stormriders.Descr: When the Khan chose to side with the Blue Wizards, many fearsome warriors came with the two Maia and none are more mysterious or feared than the women of the Uushixià clan. Defying all known warring convention, the clan sends its women to war alongside the men! These feared warriors are like a storm: their charge decimates enemy battalions when used correctly and their crossbows, gifted to them by the Orocarni, ensure that long after any archer has run out of arrows they will continue to fire deadly bolts that, though slow to fire, can punch through even the heaviest armour. This barrage of bolts is made even more deadly due to their mobility; only enemy cavalry stands a chance of catching up to these riders. They are a deadly foe that the Shadow would do well to fear, for they are well equipped to trample both its weaker hordes and pierce the armour of its elite troops.
Uushixia Stormriders.DescrShort: Uushixià tribeswomen armed with powerful Dwarven crossbows and riding chariots pulled by swift steppe horses.

Variag Horse Archers.Descr: The bow is a central part of life in Khand, when they are strong enough to pull the string, the youth of Khand begin practice. However, the vastness of the steppes of Khand meant their archers adapted to firing from the saddle. When the chieftains of Khand call, hordes of horse archers respond. Their mounts are bred for endurance and stamina and they will keeping running long after most men and horses can go no further. As such these men use 'hit and run' tactics almost invariably. Raining wave after wave of arrows, with deadly accuracy, upon their enemies. The horse archers of Khand are second only to the riders of Imladris but a lifetime of practice and perfection leaves these men vulnerable if engaged in prolonged melee. They are outfitted for manoeuvrability and speed and so use light armour and only short swords if the need arises.
Variag Horse Archers.DescrShort: Skilled horsemen, adept at firing from the saddle and outfitted for speed.

Warlords Kataphract Archers.Descr: The bow is a central part of life in Khand, when they are strong enough to pull the string, the youth of Khand begin practice. However, the vastness of the steppes of Khand has meant their archers adapted to firing from the saddle. When the chieftains of Khand call, hordes of horse archers respond. Their mounts are bred for endurance and stamina and they will keeping running long after most men and horses can go no further. As such these men use 'hit and run' tactics almost invariably. Raining wave after wave of arrows, with deadly accuracy, upon their enemies. The horse archers of Khand are second only to the riders of Imladris but a lifetime of practice and perfection leaves these men vulnerable if engaged in prolonged melee.\n\nWhen a man proves his skill in the ranks of Horse Archers, then he may be called into the fighting battalions of the Brotherhood of the Bow, one of three elite groups within Khandish life collectively known as the 'Warlord's Brotherhood'. Taking only the finest archers in to their order, they are Khand's elite bowmen and are outfitted with the finest armour Khand can produce to ensure their survival in melee and to act as a statement of their strength. "Just as night falls on the Steppes, so to do we fall on our enemies; as the serpent devours all, so to do we devour our enemies; as the shadows spare none, so to do we spare no enemy. As a silver tide we rise, in the name of Khand!" - Song of the Brotherhood
Warlords Kataphract Archers.DescrShort: Elite horsemen, adept at firing from the saddle and clad in heavy armour.

Warlords Kataphracts.Descr: Khand is a land of horsemen and many men are born in the saddle. Unlike the Rohirrim, this is more out of necessity than desire but that does not mean the men of Khand are not adept on horseback and these men are testament to that fact. After having spent a lifetime on horse and bearing the scars of countless battles, the best Khand has to offer are selected to join the Brotherhood of the Lance, one of three elite groups within Khandish life collectively known as the 'Warlord's Brotherhood'. Choosing lances over the more common Khandish spear, they are the juggernauts of the east, appearing in battle on fine mounts and wearing well crafted heavy lamellar armour, they crush all those who stand in their path. They are not as mobile as the men of Rohan and their armour slows them down but often only one charge by these formidable units is enough. They take on only the best men of the tribes and are only called into battle if absolutely necessary as their numbers are few. "Just as night falls on the Steppes, so to do we fall on our enemies; as the serpent devours all, so to do we devour our enemies; as the shadows spare none, so to do we spare no enemy. As a silver tide we rise, in the name of Khand!" - Song of the Brotherhood
Warlords Kataphracts.DescrShort: Elite horsemen wearing the heavy armour of Khand's elites and wielding deadly lances.

Nomad Warriors.Descr: The numerous tribes that have retained their independence, albeit under fealty to the Variags, draft battalions of warriors for the Khan's armies. They are not as skilled as the secretive Warlord's Brotherhood or as well equipped as the Variags' own hand picked troops but they are fierce fighters nonetheless. Despite their war fervour, loyalty and fierce bloodlust, they are still relatively lightly armoured and their ranks can be decimated by archer fire and should not be expected to hold against the heavily armoured infantry of Gondor or the Knights of Dol Amroth. These particular warriors are those who have chosen to fight on foot with round shields and heavy sabres and will usually form the bulk of Khand's infantry.
Nomad Warriors.DescrShort: Medium sword infantry, wielding keen swords and small shields but only medium armour.

Nomad Axemen.Descr: The numerous tribes that have retained their independence, albeit under fealty to the Variags, draft battalions of warriors for the Khan's armies. They are not as skilled as the secretive Warlord's Brotherhood or as well equipped as the Variags' own hand picked troops but they are fierce fighters nonetheless. Despite their war fervour, loyalty and fierce bloodlust, they are still relatively lightly armoured and their ranks can be decimated by archer fire and should not be expected to hold against the heavily armoured infantry of Gondor or the Knights of Dol Amroth. These particular warriors wield two handed axes and a charge by these men will leave even the bravest men quaking.
Nomad Axemen.DescrShort: Medium shock infantry, wielding heavy axes but only medium armour.

Variag Swordsmen.Descr: Khand has no formal military and most men go to war with whatever weapon they have practised with the most. There are exceptions to this rule however and the warriors of Khand are testament to that. When a man has served his time in the ranks of the Khandish Elites but has not lost the taste for battle, they almost always join with the Warriors of Khand. These men have seen countless battles and retain their heavy armour from their past. As the duel swords of the elites are symbolic, the warriors can no longer use them and so, to ensure they still instil fear, they have adopted heavy two handed swords. Performing as the very best dismounted shock troopers that Khand can field, they are proud of their pasts and have little fear of death, making them a truly formidable force on the battlefield. Few men survive long enough to see their service ended in Khand, making these units incredibly rare.
Variag Swordsmen.DescrShort: Heavy shock infantry, well armoured and equipped with brutal two handed swords.

Warlords Guard.Descr: Often, the field of battle is not suited to cavalry and the vast hordes of Khand have to use infantry instead, equipping their warriors with sword, spear and axe. Should a man prove his skill on the field of battle on foot then he may be called into the fighting battalions of the Brotherhood of the Axe, one of three elite groups within Khandish life collectively know as the 'Warlord's Brotherhood'. The Brotherhood of the Axe is the youngest of the four and they wear their heavy armour with pride. Opting to use an axe in honour of the great Khandish hero Hasar; Hasar fought and died in battle against Gondor in T.A 1944 but was said to have fought with the strength of 10 men; a maelstrom in the sea of men, wielding his two-handed axe with fury. In battle they also wield these mighty axes and can carve through the enemy ranks with ease, also, like all Brotherhood warriors they cover their faces so as to inspire fear. Despite their prowess, they are only called into battle if absolutely necessary as their numbers are few. "Just as night falls on the Steppes, so to do we fall on our enemies; as the serpent devours all, so to do we devour our enemies; as the shadows spare none, so to do we spare no enemy. As a silver tide we rise, in the name of Khand!" - Song of the Brotherhood
Warlords Guard.DescrShort: Heavily armoured, heavy axe wielding elites.

Khandish Hunters.Descr: Khand, lying south west of Rhûn, has been the traditional ally of the Easterlings since the time of the Wainriders. As such they supply mercenaries to the Warlords and the Lôke-Khan whenever asked. These take the form of Horsemen and adept archers. The Steppe Hunters are fast moving archers who form a perfect counter-part to the guard of the Easterlings. Outfitted with light leather lamellar and steel helmets Hunters carry composite bows and axes into battle. In times of need, the Hunters can be mounted and serve as cavalry where their skills rival those of the Lôke-Khans own elite archers; the Lôke-Nar Rim.
Khandish Hunters.DescrShort: Skilled Hunters who shower the enemy with arrows, weakening and breaking formations before the infantry move in.

Variag Bowmen.Descr: The bow is a central part of life in Khand, when they are strong enough to pull the string, the youth of Khand begin practice. These men represent the years of toil spent at perfecting skill with the bow on foot. They are not the finest archers of the vastness of the east nor are they the best fighters but they will support their cavalry brethren from afar with a ferocity rarely seen in the west.
Variag Bowmen.DescrShort: Skilled archers, armed with sturdy composite bows and protected by mail armour.

Windriders of Khand.Descr: Windriders take their name very deservedly, being the fastest unit on the face of Middle-earth. It is said amongst the tribes of Khand that when the Nazgûl came to the far east to rouse the tribes for war in Sauron's name, the Windriders outpaced them. A feat only accomplished by Glorfindel of Gondolin! The Windriders are a group of warriors who now fight for the Variag's but are descended from the first tribesmen to master horse riding. As such they have spent thousands of years closely guarding their masterful secrets and practising the art of riding. Whilst not the finest warriors of the clans they are still very skilled at fighting atop their horses and they carry fierce sabres, capable of slicing through enemies at top speed. There are none faster than the Windriders and they are a formidable foe.
Windriders of Khand.DescrShort: Lightning fast sword wielding mounted warriors.

Variag Lancers.Descr: Hailing from the south-eastern steppes of Khand, these riders follow an ancestral art of battling on horseback. These men have been trained for years with the heaviest horses found in these harsh regions, and donning with the best equipment the Khandish smithies could craft: lamellar plate armour, with a closed helmet, and a long sharp wooden lance and a small iron buckler. Their charge is among the most terrific and powerful of the warriors of the east and few enemies can withstand such tremendous power. Even the spearmen from Dol Amroth and Gondor know their fate might come if a battalion of these heavy cavalry decide to trample them.
Variag Lancers.DescrShort: Armoured heavy cavalry equipped to break enemy formations with mighty charges.

Ents.Descr: These shepherds of the forest are the answer to Yavanna's prayers on behalf of the tress of Middle-earth. Created during Arda's Spring in the First Age the Ents were intended to safe-guard the forests of the world from greedy axes and ensure the survival of Yavanna's fruits. Unfortunately Melkor's and Sauron's wars wrought great destruction upon Middle-earth's forests and by the time of the Third Age the Ents became isolated and contained to Fangorn Forest. Feeling betrayed and forgotten they care not for the wars and struggles of Middle-earth's peoples, spending their time tending to the last remnants of the ancient primeval forests. As the conflict between the Free Peoples and Sauron escalates it may soon spill out into Fangorn, the Ents' last refuge, and should that come to pass the forest shepherds' wrath may become known once more. Ents differ greatly in size, appearance and form just like the different species of trees that they guard and which they tend to resemble. The one trait all Ents share is their immense strength which is said to surpass even the mighty trolls who are said to be Morgoth's imitation of Ents. Therefore, when enraged, the apparently docile forest shepherds can turn into frightening opponents able to crush most flesh and blood creatures with a single blow or swipe of their powerful limbs. However their apathy towards anything that doesn't concern their woodland domain may make stirring them into a war-like disposition difficult.
Ents.DescrShort: Ancient forest wardens of immense strength.

Black Spiders.Descr: The Great Spiders that plague Mirkwood are the offspring of Shelob, last daughter of Ungoliant. While not as powerful as Shelob, they are still large and terrible creatures, with keen senses, darting at their prey and intelligent enough to converse and share wicked plans.The Great Spiders use their webs to trap their prey and dangle their victims from tree branches after stunning them with poison.
Black Spiders.DescrShort: Large and terrible creatures, stunning their prey with poison.

Forest Spiders.Descr: The Great Forest Spiders have made a lair in the proximity of Dol Guldur. They are the offspring of Shelob but have adapted to the forest environment over several generations. The Great Forest Spiders are not as powerful as Shelob, but they are still large and terrible creatures. They live on networks of webs which they wove among the trees. The Great Spiders also use their webs to trap their prey and dangle their victims from tree branches after stunning them with poison.
Forest Spiders.DescrShort: Large and terrible creatures, stunning their prey with poison.

Bandits.Descr: If you were ever to sit in an inn listening to stories of "strange folk wondering about" chances are those stories would be referring to these people. Whether through some misfortune, a simple a lack of virtue or perhaps outside coercion these men have taken up the mantle of the outlaw and now roam the roads in darkness searching for profitable victims. Living outside the normal society exposed to dangers that plague the lands has made these bandits hardened and gruff and there is little they wouldn't do to improve their lives. Despite their ways the fate of these men is tied to that of Eriador and war has presented them with an opportunity to both earn coin and give relief to their violent tendencies. Properly "motivated" they will turn their criminal guile and tenacity against any invading army for as long as there is some gain to be had, one way or the other.
Bandits.DescrShort: Sinister outlaws with long blades and round shields.

Oathbreakers.Descr: The Men of the Mountains, who’s King swore allegiance to Isildur and the Dúnedain in the last years of the Second Age. They had worshipped Sauron in the Dark Years before the foundation of Gondor, and when the time came for them to fulfil their oath, and fight beside Isildur against their ancient master, they broke their word, and hid in the mountains. Isildur cursed them to survive without rest until their oath was fulfilled. So they haunted the Paths of the Dead throughout the Third Age, waiting for Isildur's heir to appear and grant them the chance to fulfil their word at last.
Oathbreakers.DescrShort: Cursed by Isildur, they wait for Isildur's heir to grant them the chance to fulfil their word at last.

Rhovanion Spearmen.Descr: These men are commoners and peasants who have volunteered to join the local militias to defend towns, roads and bolster armies. Given some training and equipped with a short spear and shield, though little armour, these units are useful in defence, but cannot be expected to endure for long on an open battlefield.
Rhovanion Spearmen.DescrShort: Spearmen are commoners and peasants who fight for the freedom of their country.

Rhovanion Hunters.Descr: These villagers have been taken from their day to day lives of hunting game and instead are told to train their arrows on men, orcs, or whatever enemy needs killing. They have deft hands, are very well-practised, and know how to hide in the woods.
Rhovanion Hunters.DescrShort: Made up of villagers and ordinary folk, these men are superior hunters and are excellent at ambushes.

Rhovanion Riders.Descr: The country of Rhovanion is best suited to horses and even after the fall of the Kingdom of Rhovanion the remaining people of this land are excellent horsemen. Much of the original population either migrated north to Dale and Lake-town or west to the Éothéod. These horsemen still refuse to leave their homeland and form the last resistance against any enemies occupying their land.
Rhovanion Riders.DescrShort: Fast light cavalry with small shields and sharp spears.

Raider Warband.Descr: Orcish raiders make frequent forays into neighbouring lands, pillaging and terrorizing any poorly defended settlements. With the advent of a new war they had been tasked with probing Gondor's defences and harassing the elves of Mirkwood and Lórien, but now Sauron's conquests have taken them from their usual prowling grounds straight to the walls of Minas Tirith, Caras Galadhon, and beyond. Though their scavenged and improvised weapons and armour together with a lack of tactical sense for open warfare makes them unsuited for head on clashes with decently equipped and disciplined troops, inexperienced or overconfident commanders just might find their lines broken and overrun by the raiders' sheer numbers and beastly aggression.

Raider Skirmishers.Descr: Orcish raiders make frequent forays into neighbouring lands, pillaging and terrorizing any poorly defended settlements. With the advent of a new war they had been tasked with probing Gondor's defences and harassing the elves of Mirkwood and Lórien, but now Sauron's conquests have taken them from their usual prowling grounds straight to the walls of Minas Tirith, Caras Galadhon, and beyond. Though their scavenged and improvised weapons and armour together with a lack of tactical sense for open warfare makes them unsuited for head on clashes with decently equipped and disciplined troops, inexperienced or overconfident commanders just might find their lines broken and overrun by the raiders' sheer numbers and beastly aggression.
Raider Skirmishers.DescrShort: Lightly equipped orcs armed with throwing spears and simple melee weapons.

Farrhun Mercanaries.Descr: The lands beyond the sea of Rhûn are shrouded in total mystery to all but the most easterly of the Easterling tribes. Even the Uúshixia, Rhûn’s most exotic tribe, don’t know what the lands beyond are home to. Into this veil of mystery comes the Far-Rhûn Mercs. These men are not from a single tribe but from many, they have marched for days and months to reach the ‘rich lands’ of Middle-earth where they hope to find wealth and the promise of battle. Each man may have different cultural values to the man at his shoulder but they all agree that through Sauron, they will become famed as warriors and rich as kings. They will fight wherever the followers of Melkor have need; as long as the pay is good.
Farrhun Mercanaries.DescrShort: Mercenary warriors hailing from the far east of Middle Earth, armed with distinctive long, curved spears.

Harondor Mercenaries.Descr: Harondor is a debatable land that has passed between the hands of Harad and Gondor countless times. Harondor itself means 'Southern Gondor' but that hasn't stopped the hordes of the desert from ransacking it any chance they get. After a time, the inhabitants of Harondor have realised that neither kingdom will ever truly fight for them and so they have formed into their own battalions and they seek to sell their services to the highest bidder rather than continuously fight off a different enemy each year. These men wield the loose fitting armour of the deserts but Númenórean steel and shields made by quality smiths. These men will carve Gondorian and Haradrim alike and care only that their families are safe; and their pockets are lined...\n\nREQUIRES HARONDOR
Harondor Mercenaries.DescrShort: Seasoned mercenaries of the Harondor region, armed with swords and big shields.\n\nREQUIRES HARONDOR

Privateer Axemen.Descr:
The "tudnas" walks a lonely path. Not all men of Middle-earth have a place which they call home. There are some who tread the pathless roads, bear no claim to a hearth or kin. Whether cast adrift by sorrow's gale, marked by the exile's brand, or spurred on by a restless heart,  these men wander aimlessly from place to place.

The wilds of these lands, however, have long darkened and for a man to survive such wandering, the skills of survival must be honed to a keen edge. Those that know the lands of afar have much to tell and much to offer. Be it council, wisdom or simply the weight of an axe, there are some things only experience can offer and these men offer their experience for coin.

The vagabonds that survive long enough to purchase a mount make good use of it, in both wandering and war. Those less fortunate, wield a large two-handed axe which can cleave with ease more than just a night's firewood.
Privateer Axemen.DescrShort: Wandering vagabonds equipped with a large, two-handed axe

Privateer Cavalry.Descr:
The "tudnas" walks a lonely path. . Not all men of Middle-earth have a place which they call home. There are some who tread the pathless roads, bear no claim to a hearth or kin. Whether cast adrift by sorrow's gale, marked by the exile's brand, or spurred on by a restless heart,  these men wander aimlessly from place to place.

The wilds of these lands, however, have long darkened and for a man to survive such wandering, the skills of survival must be honed to a keen edge. Those that know the lands of afar have much to tell and much to offer. Be it council, wisdom or simply the weight of an axe, there are some things only experience can offer and these men offer their experience for coin.

Theese vagabonds that survive long enough to purchase a mount make good use of it, in both wandering and war. Those less fortunate, wield a large two-handed axe which can cleave with ease more than just a night's firewood.
Privateer Cavalry.DescrShort: Mounted warriors from the wilds of Middle-earth

Farmhand Pikemen.Descr: In the troubling times that afflict Middle-earth, none are spared from the selection of warriors to hold back the tide of enemies seeking to wipe each other out or claim dominion over all the lands. These simple farmhands are one such group of humans who will need to fight to defend their lands. Unlike other farmers of Middle-earth and lesser peasantry, these men work solely with livestock and this gives them a hardier constitution and as such, they are capable warriors. Wearing light leather armour under their farming attire, they are swift, agile and hardy but cursed with appealing morale.
Farmhand Pikemen.DescrShort: Lightly armoured but dependable farmhands from the livestock farms of Middle-earth.

Saralainn Mercenaries.Descr: Saralainn is a small 'fiefdom' to the south west of old Cardolan that has grown in power since the decline of Arnor. The men from this hard land view themselves as far greater than anything that has come from the vast plains of Enedwaith and hold themselves in high honour because of this. They have repeatedly fought against the men of Enedwaith, however after a time they began to realise that their skills could be put to better use and they began to work as mercenaries for the various lords, chiefs and merchants passing through the old port of Lond Daer. War is a profitable affair and none know this better than the mercenaries of old Saralainn. On the battlefield they wield stout bill-hooks, keen chain mail; forged with some inspiration from their connection to Cardolan, and stout round shields. They will not change the tide of battle but if there is money to be earned, these men will found nearby.\n\nREQUIRES SUDURI.
Saralainn Mercenaries.DescrShort: Battle hardened sellswords from Saralainn equipped with chain mail, and versatile bill-hooks.\n\nREQUIRES SUDURI.

Druedain Hunters.Descr: To the north of the far eastern edge of the White Mountains lies the Drúadan forest. This eerie location is seldom visited by Gondorians or Rohirrim and for good reason, the Drúedain. These men, also known as Woses or Púkelmen, have lived in the White Mountain region for centuries. They share common ancestry with the Edain but time and unknown factors has changed them into small, runt like men, who speak in a complicated tongue of grunts and noises. They have no loyalty to other men but they fiercely hunt orcs and it is this connection that allows them to sometimes fight for the Free Peoples. In battle the Woses use deadly poison arrows and use ambush and stealth to deal with their prey.
Druedain Hunters.DescrShort: Hunters from the lands of the Woses, primitively equipped but armed with lethal poisoned arrows.

Westron Ballista.Descr: These artillery pieces resemble giant crossbows on a simple wheeled carriage. They can hurl javelins with great accuracy, and the power of these machines means that their bolts can pierce any armour.
Westron Ballista.DescrShort: Resembling a giant crossbow, this powerful weapon can fling javelins a great distance, skewering men with ease.

Dwarven Ballista.Descr: These artillery pieces resemble giant crossbows on a simple wheeled carriage. They can hurl javelins with great accuracy, and the power of these machines means that their bolts can pierce any armour.
Dwarven Ballista.DescrShort: Resembling a giant crossbow, this powerful weapon can fling javelins a great distance, skewering the enemy with ease.

Elven Ballista.Descr: These artillery pieces resemble giant crossbows on a simple wheeled carriage. They can hurl javelins with great accuracy, and the power of these machines means that their bolts can pierce any armour.
Elven Ballista.DescrShort: Resembling a giant crossbow, this powerful weapon can fling javelins a great distance, skewering men with ease.

Snaga Ballista.Descr: These artillery pieces resemble giant crossbows on a simple wheeled carriage. They can hurl javelins with great accuracy, and the power of these machines means that their bolts can pierce any armour.
Snaga Ballista.DescrShort: Resembling a giant crossbow, this powerful weapon can fling javelins a great distance, skewering the enemy with ease.

Snaga Catapult.Descr: Constructed of wood and capable of flinging stones large enough to crush a man's head, the catapult is a common sight on the battlefields of Middle-earth.
Snaga Catapult.DescrShort: Older style rock-flinging wooden artillery piece. Can throw flaming and normal shots.

Westron Catapult.Descr: Constructed of wood and capable of flinging stones large enough to crush a man's head, the catapult is a common sight on the battlefields of Middle-earth.
Westron Catapult.DescrShort: Older style rock-flinging wooden artillery piece. Can throw flaming and normal shots.

Dwarven Catapult.Descr: Constructed of wood and capable of flinging stones large enough to crush a man's head, the catapult is a common sight on the battlefields of Middle-earth but, using their advanced skill as masons and craftsmen, the Dwarves have mastered the art of siege warfare and their catapults can fire grape shots, capable of cutting down any foolish enough to stand in the way and mortar shots; landing with explosive precision.
Dwarven Catapult.DescrShort: Older style rock-flinging wooden artillery piece. Can throw flaming, normal and grape shots.

Elven Catapult.Descr: Constructed of wood and capable of flinging stones large enough to crush a man's head, the catapult is a common sight on the battlefields of Middle-earth.
Elven Catapult.DescrShort: Older style rock-flinging wooden artillery piece. Can throw flaming and normal shots.

Mordor Catapult.Descr: Constructed of wood and capable of flinging stones large enough to crush a man's head, the catapult is a common sight on the battlefields of Middle-earth.
Mordor Catapult.DescrShort: Older style rock-flinging wooden artillery piece. Can throw flaming and normal shots as well as rotting meat.

Misty Mangonel.Descr: Goblins have always been cunning, clever and demonic but this has usually caused them to do little more than fight amongst themselves. Now however they have turned their attention to war and their most vile souls have put together a weapon of pure death, representing the pinnacle of goblin devilry and ingenuity: The Flame Wrangler. These monstrous machines hurl flaming barrels of oil across the plains of Middle-earth. The substances inside are highly volatile and frequently erupt in a torrent of flame and destruction in mid-air. If that is the case then the poor folk who are blanketed by this flaming rainstorm stand little chance. Should the barrels reach their targets intact then the impact with the ground causes a violent explosion that can claim 40 souls in a single shot. The only saving grace for the free peoples is that these machines are virtually useless against structures.
Misty Mangonel.DescrShort: Giant machines capable of hurling flaming barrels of death across battlefield.

Gondor Trebuchet.Descr: The counter-weight Trebuchet is an evolution of the man-powered catapults. It was introduced by the Gondorian army as an effective siege and defence engine capable of lobbing large wall-crushing boulders. The Trebuchet is also able to fling such things as burning missiles and rotten animal remains to devastate enemy units.
Gondor Trebuchet.DescrShort: Giant rock-flinging artillery piece. Capable of flaming and normal shot. Also able to fling diseased cows!

Human Boat.Descr: Longships have been in use by the men of Middle-earth for many centuries. Lacking the knowledge of the ocean that the Númenóreans brought out of the west, the lesser men rely on these simple oar powered boats to ferry troops up and down the great rivers of Middle-earth. When pressed into battle these simple vessels attempt to ram one another or rely on archer fire from the deck.
Human Boat.DescrShort: Usually used as a troop carrier. These ships carries scouting parties across Middle-earth.

Gondor Boat.Descr: The Aearsûl or 'Ocean Wind' is Gondor and Dol Amroth's workhorse boat. Acting primarily for pirate defence, coastal guard and troop movement. The Aearsûl is not well suited to the open ocean and it cannot hope to match it's stronger cousin from Umbar. However, the lesser men of Middle-earth still gaze in awe as the great swan shaped ships sail up and down the coasts of Gondor.
Gondor Boat.DescrShort: This light and manoeuvrable warship of the fleet should not be underestimated for her size.

Gondor Ship.Descr: Alcarondas means 'Castle of the Sea' in Adûnaic and this ship suits its name well. Multiple masts, like towers, rise above the decks and the ship appears like a small fortresses, with archers and highly trained mariners to defend her 'walls'. Yet she is not cumbersome but fast and relatively quick to turn in battle. An Alcarondas is only outclassed by vessels crafted by the Elven shipwrights of Lindon and the Dark Númenóreans of the south. The middlemen, however, cannot outmatch this glorious sea-going vessel. A floating monument to the Dúnedain's maritime heritage!
Gondor Ship.DescrShort: A great warship for long voyages of exploration.

Elven Boat.Descr: 'West-wings' or 'wings of the West' is the translation of this ship's name from the Ancient Tongue. Its name derives from its speed and great lightness; mariners who have sailed her likening the experience to riding the waters as if borne aloft by wings.  Though light and manoeuvrable she is still a ship of war, however, and should not be underestimated. For her size and draught she can outmatch most other vessels.
Elven Boat.DescrShort: This light and manoeuvrable warship of the Fleet should not be underestimated for her size.

Elven Ship.Descr: This heavy yet adaptable warship is the pride of Círdan himself. It can be provisioned for longer journeys than the Númerrámar, hence its name, Palarran, which means 'far-wanderer' in the High Speech of the West. There are no ships in Middle-earth that can counter the Palarran.
Elven Ship.DescrShort: This heavy warship of the fleet can outmatch any other vessel, though a Corsair Marauder will provide a challenge.

Enedwaith Boat.Descr: Dragon Boats are the command ships of the Enedwaith navy. Equipped with a keel and a double set of rowers which doubles the fighting power in melee, as all rowers onboard are also warriors. These boats carry ballista for firing grappling hooks to pull enemy ships into contact, enabling boarding actions.
Enedwaith Boat.DescrShort: A larger version of the longship, able to carry more men as well as grappling hooks for boarding actions.

Adunaim Boat.Descr: A Balukazga (war boat) will transport armies and provide some protection against pirates. Whilst simple, it is still far more suited to ocean going combat than the Longships of the lesser men.
Adunaim Boat.DescrShort: This simple boat will transport armies and provide some protection against pirates.

Adunaim Ship.Descr: The Dulgubalak (Black-ship) is similar to a cog but used by fearless admirals who mostly seek fame and fortune for their own cause. Carries many fierce corsairs armed with bows and short swords for assaulting enemy ships.
Adunaim Ship.DescrShort: A Corsair ship commanded by a fearless Admiral seeking fame and fortune!
